My heart rate spiked and I felt physically sick listening to that half-brained nonsense talk

This is why European companies prevail and American startups fail so often

Scaling without proper procedures is just a one-way ticket to bankruptcy

rawContent:
Saved a fellow female founder from killing her startup today

She has just raised $10M Series A for her AI beauty product

She was so excited, talking about scaling the team and launching in new markets

I had to stop her right there and asked - "do you have any idea what you have to do now?"

She looked confused

"You need to register with data protection authorities in every EU country you operate in. Appoint a DPO. Conduct DPIA assessments. Implement GDPR-compliant data processing agreements with every vendor"

"You'll need to localize data storage for France, Germany has different rules, and don't even get me started on cross-border data transfers post-Schrems II"

Her smile faded, and she asked how long all those things take

"If you move fast? 12-16 months. But don't rush it as you could face fines up to 4% of global revenue"

She called her investors and cancelled the fundraise

She will sort out compliance first before trying to raise again

Probably saved her company from destroying itself

Feels good to be a mentor to inexperienced founders
